  18. ‌type machtype_component =
  19.   | Val
  20.   | Addr
  21.   | Int
  22.   | Float

  24. (* - [Val] denotes a valid OCaml value: either a pointer to the beginning
  25.      of a heap block, an infix pointer if it is preceded by the correct
  26.      infix header, or a 2n+1 encoded integer.
  27.    - [Int] is for integers (not necessarily 2n+1 encoded) and for
  28.      pointers outside the heap.
  29.    - [Addr] denotes pointers that are neither [Val] nor [Int], i.e.
  30.      pointers into the heap that point in the middle of a heap block.
  31.      Such derived pointers are produced by e.g. array indexing.
  32.    - [Float] is for unboxed floating-point numbers.

  34. The purpose of these types is twofold.  First, they guide register
  35. allocation: type [Float] goes in FP registers, the other types go
  36. into integer registers.  Second, they determine how local variables are
  37. tracked by the GC:
  38.    - Variables of type [Val] are GC roots.  If they are pointers, the
  39.      GC will not deallocate the addressed heap block, and will update
  40.      the local variable if the heap block moves.
  41.    - Variables of type [Int] and [Float] are ignored by the GC.
  42.      The GC does not change their values.
  43.    - Variables of type [Addr] must never be live across an allocation
  44.      point or function call.  They cannot be given as roots to the GC
  45.      because they don't point after a well-formed block header of the
  46.      kind that the GC needs.  However, the GC may move the block pointed
  47.      into, invalidating the value of the [Addr] variable.
  48. *)

  241. ‌val iter_shallow_tail: (expression -> unit) -> expression -> bool
  242.   (** Either apply the callback to all immediate sub-expressions that
  243.       can produce the final result for the expression and return
  244.       [true], or do nothing and return [false].  Note that the notion
  245.       of "tail" sub-expression used here does not match the one used
  246.       to trigger tail calls; in particular, try...with handlers are
  247.       considered to be in tail position (because their result become
  248.       the final result for the expression).  *)

  250. ‌val map_tail: (expression -> expression) -> expression -> expression
  251.   (** Apply the transformation to an expression, trying to push it
  252.       to all inner sub-expressions that can produce the final result.
  253.       Same disclaimer as for [iter_shallow_tail] about the notion
  254.       of "tail" sub-expression. *)

  256. ‌val map_shallow: (expression -> expression) -> expression -> expression
  257.   (** Apply the transformation to each immediate sub-expression. *)
